			<title>News MS Sponsors IPython</title>
			<link>http://www.graffe.com/forums/showthread.php?75875-MS-Sponsors-IPython&amp;goto=newpost</link>
			<pubDate>Fri, 04 Oct 2013 00:21:38 GMT</pubDate>
			<description><![CDATA[https://news.ycombinator.com/item?id=6490034 
 
If I am Wolfram or Mathworks I am increasingly uncomfortable about my capacity to be relevant and very concerned. IPython (with supporting libraries) is already very good and replicates a large swathe of Mathematica's and Matlab's functionality. And,...]]></description>
			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<div><a href="https://news.ycombinator.com/item?id=6490034" target="_blank" rel="nofollow">https://news.ycombinator.com/item?id=6490034</a><br />
<br />
If I am Wolfram or Mathworks I am increasingly uncomfortable about my capacity to be relevant and very concerned. IPython (with supporting libraries) is already very good and replicates a large swathe of Mathematica's and Matlab's functionality. And, recently IPython gained interop with Julia (a numerical computing language like Octave/Matlab), which is gaining traction amongst engineers despite being relatively immature and it is extremely promising and incomparably better designed than Matlab (the PL) already (not that that is hard to do). So, it's nice to see MS providing some grant money for further IPython work as it's already an important and very useful bit of technology that keeps getting better. <br />
<br />
Mathematica has less overlap with current IPython features than Matlab though as excluding Mathematica's very nice document export functions, I am not aware of a way to embed an interactive demo within an IPython notebook like one can with Mathematica which is immensely useful in some demo situations. But, there may be a way to do that as easily, and I am just not aware of it. Google did not turn anything up though. Assuming that assertion is correct, I would be surprised if it did not make its way into IPython in the future as IPython is already in use by instructors who could take advantage of such a feature.</div>

]]></content:encoded>
