			<title>Project Grok</title>
			<link>http://www.graffe.com/forums/showthread.php?75835-Project-Grok&amp;goto=newpost</link>
			<pubDate>Wed, 25 Sep 2013 20:37:26 GMT</pubDate>
			<description>Here is a synopsis of the project without having to watch a long talk: http://bsumm.net/2012/08/11/steve-yegge-and-grok.html 
 
If you are familiar with the LLVM project, the idea is similar except for a language abstraction for code analysis/tool development. Instead of having to write both the...</description>
			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<div>Here is a synopsis of the project without having to watch a long talk: <a href="http://bsumm.net/2012/08/11/steve-yegge-and-grok.html" target="_blank" rel="nofollow">http://bsumm.net/2012/08/11/steve-yegge-and-grok.html</a><br />
<br />
If you are familiar with the LLVM project, the idea is similar except for a language abstraction for code analysis/tool development. Instead of having to write both the backend to the compiler and the front end for interacting with it for each platform (OS &amp; architecture) and how it is interacted with for every ecosystem, separate those via an intermediate language. The result is an order's of magnitude deduplication of efforts for the tools themselves and every language does not have different levels of maturity for code analysis.<br />
<br />
<div class="bbcode_container">
	<div class="bbcode_description">Quote:</div>
	<div class="bbcode_quote printable">
		<hr />
		
			<div>
				Originally Posted by <strong>Steve Yegge</strong>
				
			</div>
			<div class="message">Grok: a Language-to-client Hub<br />
 Moving from matrix to a hub-and-spoke model for editors. Eclipse, and  every IDE implementor failed software engineering 101: separate the  indexer from the GUI platform. There should be a clean separation from  the autocomplete from the GUI portion.<br />
  Each IDE becomes a &quot;thin&quot; client. Every IDE supports M languages out of the box.<br />
  <i>Side benefits:</i> Eclipse will start faster (less tooling support needed). Consistency across cross-language calls. <br />
  Crucially, consistent tools make it easier to switch languages. Devs  would then be more likely to use the best language for the job. IDE  authors can focus on presentation and editing. This leads to more  configurability, scriptability, accessibility in languages.</div>
			
		<hr />
	</div>
</div>This is by far the most interesting project being worked on in computing since the genome project to me, and it will make transferring between languages much nicer as there will be greater homogeneity with how its tools are interacted with and how much intelligence I can expect with them. I really wish that Google would make it available so that people outside Google could work on it, hopefully they will eventually and this does not become another killed project. <br />
<br />
Consider how documentation is created within source code is not consistent between languages, as a result multiple semantics have to be kept in mind if you interact with ones that do not use the same ones. Haskell uses Haddock and C (and others) uses Doxygen for instance. It's madness and wastes valuable man hours.<br />
<br />
As an example, if this project is successful one could change between Java and Rust with no parity in toolchain maturity once the backend for Rust with Grok was implemented, and the toolchain available to interact with a language is at least (and to me a lot more important) than the language itself when deciding what to use for a task. <br />
<br />
It has important implications for refactoring and automatic and intelligent code updating as well, which would be a huge boon for working with very old code base with non-static language standards or just changing &quot;rules&quot; for the project's code, such as if you have a person that is militant about 80 char width lines or an angry e-mail/desk visit will ensue. Even keeping formatting consistent is not something that is consistent across languages when there should really be a one tool to rule them all to do so that understands the code itself. Gofmt is an example of such a tool but it is specific to Go. Quickcheck is another example; that is of huge benefit but is most well done in Haskell, a tool which would benefit everyone.</div>

]]></content:encoded>
