			<title><![CDATA[iTunes & TuneUp]]></title>
			<link>http://www.graffe.com/forums/showthread.php?75800-iTunes-amp-TuneUp&amp;goto=newpost</link>
			<pubDate>Thu, 19 Sep 2013 05:55:53 GMT</pubDate>
			<description><![CDATA[Has anyone else used TuneUp? 
 
Basically, when the iPod classic first came out, a good friend of mine got one as a christmas gift - back when they were around the $200+ price range. I thought such an investment for an mp3 player was ridiculous, I think I'd purchased one or two of those simple USB...]]></description>
			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<div>Has anyone else used TuneUp?<br />
<br />
Basically, when the iPod classic first came out, a good friend of mine got one as a christmas gift - back when they were around the $200+ price range. I thought such an investment for an mp3 player was ridiculous, I think I'd purchased one or two of those simple USB Memory sticks with a play button and a couple other controls on it for ~$20. At the time, I thought it was all that was necessary, weighing an ability to recharge and not having to change batteries manually as amenities that just weren't worth it.<br />
<br />
However, I was quite amazed at the iTunes ability to sort and categorize different mp3 naming norms. Beastie_Boys-Intergalactic and Beastie Boys - Intergalactic were placed into similar directories, and mp3s were organized rather well. <br />
<br />
I decided to buy an iPod classic of my own about 3 years ago. I was not impressed with so many redundant directories, so I did some searching and discovered TuneUp. I still wasn't especially impressed, but I decided to purchase the program with a lifetime version and was quite satisfied with the results. THey were slow, but it was still easier than going through 40 or 50 gigs of mp3s myself. I also liked that it could play videos, at the time. The iPad had not yet really made a reason to spend so much money as a video player, to me, and I figured it would be a passing fad. <br />
<br />
Day in and Day out, my hard-labor based job went by so much easier with some headphones and a charged iPod. I Loved how long the battery lasted, but still, I had the same problem from the get go - so many duplicate and redundant entries. I was too lazy to really sit down with the TUneUp program. <br />
<br />
NOW, finally, the TuneUp program has a single button for doing all of the 3 features (delete redundant files, grab correct file information, analyze sound against a song database) and am very impressed. It still is nowhere near perfect, but the purchase price of $30 3 years ago has continued to appreciate. <br />
<br />
What is the best program on the market that does this? I&quot;ll go ahead and put it out there that I have mp3s from years of collection back during the napster era that total a tremendous amount more than what I've purchased over iTunes. <br />
<br />
I would use my phone as my mp3 device, but it really is a waste of space, in my opinion - photos, video, and general app data is so much worth while in the big picture, and Pandora is more than adequate for when i want to listen to new music through my headphones. <br />
<br />
Any recommendations for an alternative?</div>

]]></content:encoded>
