			<title>DTrace</title>
			<link>http://www.graffe.com/forums/showthread.php?75787-DTrace&amp;goto=newpost</link>
			<pubDate>Sun, 15 Sep 2013 21:03:35 GMT</pubDate>
			<description><![CDATA[I've been using DTrace some lately, and it has absolutely blown me away in its intelligence and utility.  
 
It is like I have unlocked a way to communicate directly with and grok the Matrix, and is a game changing utility for debugging and profiling software on par with Valgrind in its game...]]></description>
			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<div>I've been using DTrace some lately, and it has absolutely blown me away in its intelligence and utility. <br />
<br />
It is like I have unlocked a way to communicate directly with and grok the Matrix, and is a game changing utility for debugging and profiling software on par with Valgrind in its game changing usefulness. <br />
<br />
The need for using print statements or debugging flags is a thing of the past and it is a joy to use.<br />
<br />
The big time bonus is that unlike Valgrind, DTrace is useful in every language and can be used provided someone takes the time to add bindings to DTrace within that language, so it exists for Java, all the C families, etc.<br />
<br />
As an example, such exists for Erlang despite neither Sun or Oracle originally targeting that and while abandoned now a modest attempt exists for Haskell (notably this would be very useful to complete as Haskell is constantly blamed for having shitty debugging tools).<br />
<br />
It was originally a Solaris only utility, but it has been ported to FreeBSD, QNX, OS X (with some slight gimping because Apple is a soup nazi and hate fun), and for the most part by Oracle to their own non-free version of Linux.  <br />
<br />
For licensing reasons including this in the Linux kernel directly allegedly would be incompatible with the open source license that Sun (or was it Oracle) released Solaris and its userland tools like DTrace too, so for that reason Linux has something similar but not as great in the form of SystemTap.  <br />
<br />
However, here is the interesting bit. Despite the shackles would be licenses and patents would place on implementing DTrace in Linux, one can do so in a 1:1 way without violating the various mechanisms Oracle has placed upon the software through some trickery about how it is loaded. A work in progress of DTrace on Linux that will allow usage of it outside of Oracle's Linux distro is here: <a href="https://github.com/dtrace4linux/linux" target="_blank" rel="nofollow">https://github.com/dtrace4linux/linux</a><br />
<br />
Now, I say all of that to ask this: DTrace is an amazing bit of software, and it is game changing at all levels of programming and pretty much all languages; however, despite this instead of throwing significant weight behind fully realizing DTrace on Linux through helping out the developer working towards having it fully ported over for usage with all other Linux distros work continues to focus on the less useful, less performant SytemTap. <br />
<br />
While SystemTap has a nicer license for libre software enthusiasts, a large swathe of Linux users and Linux using companies give zero fucks about such things and are happy to utilize all possible software based on its technical merits alone, and there are a lot of corporations which pay for developers to work on the Linux kernel for things they need, which is awesome and everything but it is a means to an end rather than a philosophical bent for them.<br />
<br />
The question is, why does Red Hat and others continue to work on SystemTap rather than reaching parity with DTrace on Linux? The one advantage something other than DTrace could have is not using a new programming language specific to the tool and only used for Solaris derived tools (it is called D but it's not the same as the D language that Walter Bright created <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/D_%28disambiguation%29#Computing" target="_blank" rel="nofollow">https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/D_%28d...n%29#Computing</a>), but other than that everything is gravy.<br />
<br />
I would like to see an embedded DSL in Python or some other wide spread language used for it instead of having to grok yet-another-language to utilize yet-another-tool. D is not hard, I just try to be as lazy as possible and avoid relearning the same functions over and over, which is why I largely trend towards cross platform (and ideally open source) tools as much as possible regardless of their initial time cost. Plus keeping yet-another-language in my head is an obnoxious redundancy that I would like to eliminate.<br />
<br />
I also wish ZFS (<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ZFS" target="_blank" rel="nofollow">https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ZFS</a>) would be more widely used, especially that Apple would switch to it over their own proprietary and less well designed FS. ZFS makes a lot of really brilliant decisions is why I would like this and HFS+ is about as awesome as Windows 3.1 in comparison. Interestingly they had a WIP version of this but abandoned it for no apparent reason, possibly they got in a dick measuring match with Oracle over it though, who knows with them.<br />
<br />
Basically, Solaris has/had some really cool shit in it despite its relatively short lived hoorah and is another example of technical merit being insufficient for market relevance in IT, aggressively stealing that cool shit so it can be used across multiple platforms for great justice would be stellar. <br />
<br />
In my ideal universe where I am a billionaire pilanthropist I would buy Nuance, Hex-Ray, Lispworks, Vitanuova, and Oracle and make Lispworks' IDE, ARM, IDA Pro (nothing like this exists outside of Hex Ray that is as expansive in scope afaik), Solaris and its associated tools like DTrace, Dragon Naturally Speaking, and Inferno OS available under a libre license and push Plan 9/Inferno OS like mad as it is brilliantly executed and takes the UNIX paradigm of composable tools with an everything is a file concept to its logical conclusion. Alas I do not have magical fantasy to reality instantaneous dust, but those technologies are fucking sweet.</div>

]]></content:encoded>
